# ═══════════════════════════════════════
# Unshelv'd — Environment Variables
# Copy this to .env and fill in your values
# ═══════════════════════════════════════

# ── Database ──
# Local dev (with docker-compose):
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://unshelvd:unshelvd_dev@localhost:5432/unshelvd
# AWS RDS (production) — fetched from Secrets Manager at deploy time:
# DATABASE_URL=postgresql://unshelvd:<PASSWORD>@<RDS_ENDPOINT>:5432/unshelvd?sslmode=require

# ── Server ──
# Generate a strong random secret: openssl rand -hex 32
SESSION_SECRET=change-me-to-a-random-string
PORT=8080

# Base URL of the web app — used in email links (password reset, email verification, etc.)
# Set this to your public domain so emails contain correct URLs.
# Falls back to https://unshelvd.koshkikode.com when not set.
# PUBLIC_APP_URL=https://unshelvd.koshkikode.com

# ── Admin (optional overrides; otherwise auto-generated/rotated on each seed run) ──
# ADMIN_USERNAME=your-chosen-username
# ADMIN_EMAIL=your-email@example.com
# ADMIN_PASSWORD=YourSecurePassword!123

# ── Demo users (optional, auto-generated if not set) ──
# DEMO_PASSWORD=DemoUserPassword!123

# ── Stripe (payments) ──
# Get all three values from https://dashboard.stripe.com
#
# STRIPE_SECRET_KEY        — "Secret key" on the API Keys page
#                            Starts with sk_live_ (production) or sk_test_ (test mode)
#                            ⚠️  Never commit this. In production, store in AWS Secrets Manager.
#
# STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET    — "Signing secret" shown after creating a webhook endpoint
#                            Endpoint URL: https://unshelvd.koshkikode.com/api/webhooks/stripe
#                            Events to send: payment_intent.succeeded, payment_intent.payment_failed,
#                                            account.updated, transfer.failed, charge.refunded
#                            Starts with whsec_
#                            ⚠️  Never commit this. In production, store in AWS Secrets Manager.
#
# VITE_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY — "Publishable key" on the API Keys page
#                            Starts with pk_live_ (production) or pk_test_ (test mode)
#                            Safe to expose to the browser — not a secret.
#                            In production, pass as a build-time env var to the Amplify Hosting build.
#
# Leave all three unset (or blank) to run without payments (dev/demo mode).
STRIPE_SECRET_KEY=sk_test_...
STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET=whsec_...
VITE_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=pk_test_...

# ── Mobile App API URL ──
# Set this when building native apps to point to your production server.
# Required by verify-env.ts when VITE_TARGET=android or VITE_TARGET=ios.
# VITE_API_URL=https://unshelvd.koshkikode.com

# Build target — used by scripts/verify-env.ts and passed automatically by
# the npm cap:build:android / cap:build:ios scripts.  Do NOT set in .env;
# set on the command line only (e.g. VITE_TARGET=android npm run build).
# Valid values: web (default) | android | ios
# VITE_TARGET=web

# ── Affiliate (ThriftBooks — Impact affiliate program) ──
# VITE_THRIFTBOOKS_AFF_ID=your-impact-affiliate-id

# ── Amazon S3 (profile images) ──
# When set, avatar and cover images are stored in this S3 bucket instead of
# being kept as base64 data URIs in the database.
#
# 1. Create a bucket (or use an existing one), in your chosen AWS region:
#      aws s3api create-bucket --bucket your-bucket-name --region ca-central-1
#
# 2. Disable "Block Public Access" for this bucket and attach a bucket policy
#    that grants public read on the upload prefixes (avatars/* and covers/*),
#    OR front the bucket with CloudFront and serve images through CloudFront.
#
# 3. Grant your App Runner / ECS task role s3:PutObject and s3:DeleteObject
#    on the bucket (the SDK uses the default credential provider chain).
#
# 4. Locally: run `aws configure` or export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID /
#    AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY in your shell.
#    When unset, the upload endpoint falls back to echoing the data URI (dev mode).
#
# AWS_REGION=ca-central-1
# S3_BUCKET_NAME=your-bucket-name
#
# CloudFront CDN in front of the bucket (recommended for production):
# When set, publicUrl() returns CDN URLs (https://cdn.<domain>/<key>) instead
# of the raw S3 URL. The bucket can then keep "Block Public Access" ON and
# only allow reads from the CloudFront Origin Access Control (OAC).
# Existing rows with raw S3 URLs continue to work — both URLs serve the
# same underlying object.
# CDN_BASE_URL=https://cdn.koshkikode.com

# ── Email (transactional) ──
# Unshelv'd sends emails for password resets, offers, transactions, etc.
#
# SMTP example (Amazon SES — recommended for production):
# SMTP_HOST=email-smtp.ca-central-1.amazonaws.com
# SMTP_PORT=587
# SMTP_USER=your-ses-smtp-username      # generated in the SES console
# SMTP_PASS=your-ses-smtp-password      # ⚠️ store in AWS Secrets Manager in prod
# EMAIL_FROM=Unshelv'd <noreply@koshkikode.com>
#
# Generic SMTP (any provider):
# SMTP_HOST=smtp.your-provider.com
# SMTP_PORT=587
# SMTP_USER=your-smtp-user
# SMTP_PASS=your-smtp-password
# EMAIL_FROM=Unshelv'd <noreply@koshkikode.com>
#
# If your DNS is in Route 53, add your SMTP provider's SPF/DKIM records there.
# Alternative: configure email via admin panel (Settings → Email) at runtime.
# When unconfigured, emails are printed to the console in development.

# ── Ads (optional) ──
# VITE_ADSENSE_CLIENT=ca-pub-XXXXXXXXXX

# ── PayPal (optional alternative payment method) ──
# Configure via the admin panel (Settings → Payments) at runtime, OR set env vars here.
# PayPal is disabled by default; enable it in the admin panel once credentials are set.
#
# PAYPAL_CLIENT_ID=Aabc...         ← from https://developer.paypal.com → My Apps & Credentials
# PAYPAL_CLIENT_SECRET=EFgh...     ← ⚠️ Never commit this. Store in AWS Secrets Manager in prod.
# PAYPAL_WEBHOOK_ID=xxxxx          ← Webhook ID from PayPal Developer Dashboard
#                                    Endpoint URL: https://unshelvd.koshkikode.com/api/webhooks/paypal
#                                    Event: PAYMENT.AUTHORIZATION.VOIDED
# (default mode is "sandbox"; set paypal_mode=live in admin panel for production)
